This V2 folds in three things since the last pass. The funnel now shows its full shape, including the social teaser tier that feeds it. The band and the buyer's capacity are pulled apart into two independent axes, because a person's zone reflects their story and their goals, never their budget. And the anchor that pairs with each result is now flexible across your three rungs of core IP, not fixed to the Field Guide.

**The funnel first, because the teasers change where the top of it sits.**

# **Section One: The Funnel, Top to Bottom**

Your own materials describe a two-tier funnel, Start Here and Go Deeper, with a layer of social teasers above both. Here is the whole shape in one view.

| **LAYER** | **WHAT IT IS** | **ROLE** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Social teasers (6)** | Short, shareable, 5 to 10 minutes on a phone. Each gives a real result and points to one instrument. | The social face. Opens the door, drives traffic to Start Here and Go Deeper. |
| **Start Here (free)** | The Quick Leadership Assessment. Free, five minutes, captures an email, with the one question you read yourself. | The free front door and email capture. The Leadership Quick-Check teaser is its social face, not a rival. |
| **Go Deeper (purchased)** | Personal Narrative, Next-Gen, Org Leadership Complete, and Narrative Edge for Leaders & Orgs. | The paid or bundled instruments. The other five teasers each preview one of these. |
| **Engagements** | The Trust(ed) Co-Author session and program, advisory, and Storyteller in Residence. | The work itself. A qualified result routes here through a conversation. |

## **The collision the five zones resolve**

Underneath, the instruments still speak different band languages, and none matches the five-zone language your videos, result pages, and Kit tags already run on. The teasers add a third variation, each using three coarse bands. A person can score Emerging Narrator on the instrument, Police Report Seller on a teaser, and get routed to a Story Emerging video. Three labels, one person. The five zones, used as the single routing key, end that. The teasers can stay coarse on the surface and still route by tier underneath.

# **Section Two: Five Zones, Confirmed**

**Confirmed: **five zones are canonical: Story At Risk, Story Emerging, Story Drift, Story Developing, Story Aligned. You have already built five async videos, five result pages, and five Kit tags. Five it is.

Behind the scenes, the five zones are the one key for the code, the tags, the automations, and the analytics, so you can see every person in one view no matter which instrument or teaser they entered through. Forward facing, the same five names appear across the leader, org, and personal instruments, with the result copy doing the audience adaptation. Next-Gen is the single exception: it keeps Character-to-Author language, mapped one to one onto the five tiers.

# **Section Three: Two Axes, Pulled Apart**

This is the correction from the last pass. The band and the buyer's capacity are independent. The band reflects where the story is and what the person wants. Capacity reflects what they can fund. The two meet to produce a recommendation, but neither defines the other.

## **Axis one: the band (state plus objective)**

The assessment returns the zone, the read of the current state. A short objective question returns the ambition, where they want the story to go. Together they decide the kind of work, the engagement, the depth. Funds play no part in setting the band. A Story Aligned founder with no budget is still Story Aligned.

## **Axis two: capacity (inferred, independent)**

Capacity is read separately and quietly, inferred from role, organization size, and timeframe, never asked as a budget question on a free assessment. It sets the format and price point the person can actually reach for the work their band calls for.

## **Where they meet: the flexible anchor plus a product**

Every result still pairs an anchor with a product, so nothing dead-ends. But the anchor is no longer always the Field Guide. It flexes across your three rungs of core IP, chosen for fit:

- The Narrative Edge, the full book, for newcomers and readers who want the whole argument first.

- The condensed go-between, for those who want more than the book but are not yet ready for the full workbook. (Title and positioning still to confirm.)

- The Field Guide, for those ready to do the work with the instrument in hand.

*So the recommendation reads: the right anchor for this reader, paired with the product or engagement that matches their band and their capacity. Under-funded buyers settle on the retail anchor as their ceiling. Funded buyers pass through it as their on-ramp. Same IP, different role.*

